import pandas as pd
from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def show_figure(df, y, model):
    feature_names = df.columns
    labels = y.unique()
    plt.figure(figsize = (15,10))
    a = tree.plot_tree(model,
        feature_names = feature_names,
        class_names = labels,
        rounded = True,
        filled = True,
        fontsize=8)
    plt.show()

Explanation¶

We can see from the accuracy above that one level decision tree cannot give a better accuracy than multi-level decision tree normally. In one level decision tree, we are actually using only one feature to classify it. If this feature is selected with a pretty good information gain, it works well, like the first dataset. But normally one feature cannot classify the data properly like the second dataset. With multi-level decision tree, we can classify the data with not only one features, which gives more information gain. So it normally can provide better accuracy.

import numpy as np

def hold_out_val(X, Y, min_samples_leaf):
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.34, random_state=10)
    clf = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', min_samples_leaf=min_samples_leaf)
    clf = clf.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Yp = clf.predict(X_test)
    return accuracy_score(Y_test,Yp)

def plot_diagram(x,y):
    y_min = np.argmin(y)
    y_max = np.argmax(y)
    show_min='['+str(x[y_min])+', '+str(y[y_min])+']'
    show_max='['+str(x[y_max])+', '+str(y[y_max])+']'

    plt.plot(x[y_max],y[y_max],'x')
    plt.plot(x[y_min],y[y_min],'x')
    plt.plot(x,y)
    plt.annotate(show_max,xy=(x[y_max],y[y_max]),xytext=(x[y_max],y[y_max]))
    plt.annotate(show_min,xy=(x[y_min],y[y_min]),xytext=(x[y_min],y[y_min]))
    plt.show()

Explanation¶

Region of overfitting: the first peak in the graph Region of optimality: around the second peak in the graph Region of underfitting: after the second peak

  • When min_samples_leaf is small, the tree needs to classify every single or very few samples in a leaf, which will produce a lot of features in classification. And this makes this tree fits the training set extremely well, like how it is shown in multi-level decision tree. So in this case it is overfitting.
  • And when min_samples_leaf becomes larger, the branches of the tree is less. Here the decision tree chooses the features with higher information gain to fork without classify the data too much. And it has pretty good (or even the best) accuracy here. So in this region it is optimality.
    • The following code and diagram shows the decision tree with min_samples_leaf = 41 which gives the best accuracy in the first dataset. We can see that the depth and branches of the tree is reasonable.
  • But if min_samples_leaf becomes even larger, it's hard to only choose very few features to fork the tree. Although these nodes obtain very high information gains, their entropy is also very high. This makes the data not fully classified, like how it is shown in one-level decision tree. So in this case it is underfitting.
